issue_body:
## Description

The `on()` method in `src/plugin/managers/event-manager.ts` contains an unreachable else branch that can be safely removed to improve code clarity.

## Current Implementation

```typescript
on(event: string, callback: (...args: unknown[]) => void): void {
  if (!event || typeof callback !== 'function') {
    console.error('Invalid event name or callback provided');
    return;
  }

  if (!this.eventListeners.has(event)) {
    this.eventListeners.set(event, []);  // Line 14: Always sets empty array
  }
  const listeners = this.eventListeners.get(event);
  if (listeners) {
    listeners.push(callback);  // Line 18: This always executes
  } else {
    this.eventListeners.set(event, [callback]);  // Lines 20-21: UNREACHABLE
  }
}
```

## Why It's Unreachable

After line 14 executes and sets `event` to an empty array `[]` in the Map, the `get(event)` call on line 16 will **always** return that array (never `undefined`). This means the condition `if (listeners)` on line 17 will always be truthy, making the else branch on lines 20-21 unreachable.

## Suggested Refactor

```typescript
on(event: string, callback: (...args: unknown[]) => void): void {
  if (!event || typeof callback !== 'function') {
    console.error('Invalid event name or callback provided');
    return;
  }

  if (!this.eventListeners.has(event)) {
    this.eventListeners.set(event, []);
  }
  this.eventListeners.get(event)!.push(callback);
}
```

## Benefits

- ✅ Removes dead code
- ✅ Simplifies logic flow
- ✅ Maintains identical functionality
- ✅ Uses non-null assertion operator safely (guaranteed to exist after line 14)

## Context

This observation was identified during comprehensive test coverage work in PR #7320. The current implementation functions correctly; this is purely a code quality improvement.

**Related PR:** #7320
**File:** `src/plugin/managers/event-manager.ts`
**Lines:** 16-23

## Priority

Low - Code quality improvement, not a functional bug.

