issue_body:
### Describe the Bug

I started discussing about my woes with reverse proxying Karakeep here: https://github.com/karakeep-app/karakeep/issues/1557#issuecomment-2974599361.
For starters, the fact that it doesn't allow to configure base URL is most definitely not optimal but ok, I tried working around it.

Now I have a working solution for external access, through mydomain.duckdns.org, and a working solution from my LAN when accessing Karakeep from mydomain.duckdns.org on:

Web browser from any device
iOS app on an iPad Pro 12.9" 2nd gen.

The Android app refuses to connect to the duckdns subdomain when accessing it from the LAN. Log options are pretty much non existant, so I don't know what's actually happening. Using the debug button  goes to "Running connection test..." and stays there for a long while before spitting out:

Network connection failed: Failed to connecto to mydomain.duckdns.org/x.x.x.x:443 where x.x.x.x is my external IP, with nginx reverse proxying to https on port 443.

On the same exact device, if I access https://mydomain.duckdns.org from a web browser, Karakeep works perfectly. Both from the LAN and from mobile data outside the LAN. It's just the app that does not work on the LAN. If I connect to the numeric internal IP, it works.

To sum up:

Web browser, whatever device/browser works fine on both LAN and outside the LAN.
iPad app works fine on both LAN and outside the LAN.
Android app works fine outside the LAN, doesn't work with duckdns from inside the LAN, works when accessing numeric internal IP address.

As my smartphone is Android, I can't log out and login every time I come and go from my home...

### Steps to Reproduce

I detailed everything above. This is my nginx conf file

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    listen [::]:443 ssl;
    server_name mydomain.duckdns.org;  

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/mydomain.duckdns.org/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/mydomain.duckdns.org/privkey.pem;
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;

    # Karakeep served from the root
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:3000/;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name mydomain.duckdns.org;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

### Expected Behaviour

I expect the Karakeep Android app to work from both inside and outside the LAN using a duckdns subdomain, considering a web browser on the same device (or the iOS app on an iPad)  is perfectly capable of accessing the same server from both inside and outside the LAN, using a duckdns subdomain.

Please do not close this issue. There is provably something different in how the iOS app and/or a web browser handle things when compared to the Andr

